--- In junit@yahoogroups.com, &quot;Kris Henderson&quot; &lt;khenderson@p...&gt; wrote:
&gt; I have a method that when called creates a thread and does all its work
&gt; in the new thread.  It looks kind of like this:
&gt; 
&gt; public void doSomething()
&gt; {
&gt;     Thread requestThread = new Thread()
&gt;     {
&gt;         public void run()
&gt;         {
&gt;             fireStartEvent();
&gt; 
&gt;             //do some stuff that takes a long time
&gt; 
&gt;             fireDoneEvent();
&gt;         }
&gt;     };
&gt;     requestThread.start();
&gt; }

Is there some reason you can&#39;t test the run() method separately from
the threading?  I don&#39;t see anything in the snippets provided that
would prevent this. Is OperationAdapter dependent on having events
fired from an active thread?  

You&#39;d have to extract a named class to hold the run method.  Then your
test would look something like:

public void testRun()
{
    m_eventCount = 0;
    final MockService service = new MockService();
    DoSomthingRunner runner(service);
    service.addOperationListener(new OperationAdapter()
    {
        public void operationUpdate(OperationEvent event)
        {
            m_eventCount += 1;
        }
    });

    runner.run();

    assertEquals(2, m_eventCount);
}

Questions: 
Do you trust Thread?
If run() is tested separately, can you trust service.doSomething() to
start the thread?

You could give the service a RunnerFactory (and a MockRunnerFactory
for testing) if you feel it is worth the effort.
